# i18n (EN/MN) content across backend, admin, frontend

## Context

Blog, Partner, and Destination content (titles, descriptions, itinerary text, etc.) is
currently stored and served as flat strings in a single language. The site needs to
serve English and Mongolian versions of this content. The user proposed a 3-phase plan
(backend → admin → frontend); research against the actual codebase confirmed most of it
but found real gaps (missing admin GET routes for 2 of 3 models, an incorrect Mongo
dot-notation claim, unaddressed nested content, and an underspecified rich-text UI). This
plan is the corrected version, with open questions resolved by the user:

- **Itinerary** (`Destination.Itinerary[].{Title,Description,Activities,Meals}`) becomes
  translatable — it's the actively-edited day-by-day content added this session.
- **Partner.Products** stays a plain (non-translatable) string per product — not
  converted in this pass.
- **Blog.Body** stays untouched — it's not exposed in `BlogForm.tsx` today (only
  `Content` is edited), so there's nothing to convert.
- **`Partner.Name` / `Destination.Name`** stay plain strings (treated as proper nouns),
  not translated.
- **Rich text i18n** (`Blog.Content`, `Destination.Overview`): mount one `RichTextEditor`
  Tiptap instance per locale, all mounted simultaneously, switched via CSS
  show/hide on the active tab (avoids losing editor state on tab switch).
- **Migration**: a one-off Go script under `cmd/migrate-i18n/`, run manually by the user
  against the live Atlas cluster (`MONGO_URI`/`MONGO_DB=eandstravel`) — not run
  automatically by me.

Implementation proceeds in the same order the user specified: backend first (everything
else depends on it), then admin, then frontend. Given the size, treat each phase as a
checkpoint — verify the backend compiles/serves correctly before starting admin, etc.

